===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|croke|lang=enm}}, {{term|crok|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} *{{term||crōc|hook, bend, crook|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*krōkaz||bend, hook}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*greg-||tracery, basket, bend}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|kreuk||a bend, fold, wrinkle|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|kroke|lang=gml}}, {{term|krake||fold, wrinkle|lang=gml}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|krog||crook, hook|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|krok||crook, hook|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|krókur||hook|lang=is}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[bend]]; [[turn]]; [[curve]]; [[curvature]]; a [[flexure]].
#: ''She held the baby in the '''crook''' of her arm.''
#* Phaer
#*: through lanes, and '''crooks''', and darkness
# A bending of the knee; a [[genuflection]].
# A [[bent]] or curved part; a curving piece or portion (of anything).
#: ''the '''crook''' of a cane''
#*{{quote-book|year=1907|author=[[w:Robert W. Chambers|Robert Chambers]]
|title=The Younger Set
|chapter=1/2|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL8127246W
|passage=It was flood-tide along Fifth Avenue ; motor, brougham, and victoria swept by on the glittering current&nbsp;;&nbsp;[&hellip;]&nbsp;; young men&nbsp;[&hellip;], silk-hatted, frock-coated, the '''crooks''' of their walking sticks tucked up under their left arms, passed on the Park side.}}
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[lock]] or [[curl]] of hair.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[gibbet]].
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A support beam consisting of a post with a cross-beam resting upon it; a bracket or truss consisting of a vertical piece, a horizontal piece, and a strut.
# A [[shepherd's crook]]; a [[staff]] with a semi-circular bend ("hook") at one end used by [[shepherd]]s.
#* '''1970''', ''The New English Bible with the Apocrypha, Oxford Study Edition'', published 1976, Oxford University Press, ''Psalms'' 23-4, page 583:
#*: Even though I walk through a / valley dark as death / I fear no evil, for thou art with me, / thy staff and thy '''crook''' are my / comfort.
# A bishop's staff of office.
# An [[artifice]]; a [[trick]]; a [[contrivance]].
#* Cranmer
#*: for all your brags, hooks, and '''crooks'''
# A person who steals, lies, cheats or does other dishonest or illegal things; a criminal.
#* '''1973''' November 17, [[w:Richard Nixon|Richard Nixon]], reported 1973 November 18, ''The Washington Post'', [http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/watergate/articles/111873-1.htm ''Nixon Tells Editors, ‘I'm Not a Crook’''],
#*: "People have got to know whether or not their President is a '''crook'''. Well, I′m not a '''crook'''. I′ve earned everything I′ve got."
# A [[pothook]].
#* Sir Walter Scott
#*: as black as the '''crook'''
# {{context|music|lang=en}} A small tube, usually curved, applied to a trumpet, horn, etc., to change its pitch or key.

